{"questionId":"19661","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows a ball attached to the end of a spring, which is suspended from a ceiling.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/2d39eeda991d86574d6ffa92f93ff4ee199970b1.png\"></p>\n<p>The height, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> metres, of the ball above the ground at time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> seconds after being released can be modelled by the function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that the ball takes <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> seconds to return to its initial height above the ground for the first time.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p>the ball is released from its maximum height and returns there a period later&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>R1</strong></p>\n<p>the period is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong> A1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>attempts to solve&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;M1</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;A1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>so it takes <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> seconds for the ball to return to its initial position for the first time&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>AG</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19661","referenceCode":"EXN.1.SL.TZ0.9c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that the ball takes 2 seconds to return to its initial height above the ground for the first time.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.7—Circular functions: graphs, composites, transformations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}